        <!-- The City Changes -->
        <section>
            <h2>The City Changes</h2>

            <p>
                When the sun slips below the horizon, the city exhales. Streets once crowded
                with urgency soften into reflective corridors. Neon signs flicker like
                constellations, and every shadow tells a quieter story.
            </p>

            <p>
                Buildings seem taller at night, their windows glowing like distant stars.
                The familiar becomes strange, and the ordinary begins to feel cinematic.
            </p>

            <blockquote>
                <p>
                    “At night, the city becomes a living thing — breathing, watching, waiting.”
                </p>
            </blockquote>
        </section>

        <!-- The People -->
        <section>
            <h2>The People</h2>

            <p>
                Those who remain after midnight are not rushing anywhere. They move slowly,
                deliberately, as if aware that the city belongs to them now.
            </p>

            <h3>Wanderers</h3>
            <p>
                These are the souls who drift through empty streets with no destination,
                guided only by curiosity and the hum of streetlights.
            </p>

            <h3>Observations After Midnight</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Footsteps echo louder than thoughts</li>
                <li>Windows tell stories without words</li>
                <li>The night feels honest</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- After Hours -->
        <section>
            <h2>After Hours</h2>

            <p>
                Time stretches differently after midnight. Minutes linger. Silence speaks.
                The city no longer demands attention — it invites reflection.
            </p>

            <p>
                In these hours, the city is not a place of transit, but of presence.
            </p>
        </section>

